echarty

Minimal R/Shiny Interface to Echarts.js

 

Crosstalk

Crosstalk is about selections. Multiple R htmlwidgets can share a common dataset and exchange record selections. Since all widgets have the data already, the exchange transfers only keys (record IDs). On a more basic level, this is a mechanism of keys exchange between multiple JavasScript libraries on the same web page.
In R Markdown documents the dataset is frozen, in Shiny applications the dataset could be replaced.
Here is the R Markdown dataflow: RStudio(opt.) open .Rmd file ► embed data + R-code ► Knit .Rmd ► get .html ► host anywhere.
Library htmlwidgets takes care of gathering your data,code and libraries into one chunk exported later by knitr in HTML format.

Crosstalk provides two types of cross-widget interactions - brushing and filtering selections.
The example below uses several external crosstalk controls. Their capabilities are summarized here, R means receive and S means send.

Widget Filter S Filter R Brush S Brush R Filter Effect R Brush Effect R
filter_checkbox ✔ - - -
filter_slider ✔ - - -
datatable - ✔ ✔ ✔ show, hide show, hide
d3scatter - ✔ ✔ ✔ show, hide show, hide
echarty ✔ ✔ ✔ ✔ color, shape, etc. highlight, downplay
🔻 View code 
library(crosstalk); library(d3scatter); library(DT); library(htmltools)
library(echarty); library(dplyr); library(tibble);
styl <- 'width:50%;display:block;float:left;'
sdf <- mtcars %>% rownames_to_column(var='name') %>% relocate(mpg,wt)
sdf <- SharedData$new(sdf)

p <- sdf %>% ec.init(height=500, title=list(text="echarty 2D"))
p$x$opts$xAxis$scale <- TRUE
p$x$opts$yAxis$scale <- TRUE
p$x$opts <- append(p$x$opts, list(
   toolbox = list(feature=list(brush=list(ey=''))),
   brush = list(brushLink='all', throttleType='debounce'),
   dataZoom = list(type='inside'),
   tooltip = list(formatter = htmlwidgets::JS("function(params){return params.value[2];}"))
))
p$x$opts$series[[1]] = append(p$x$opts$series[[1]], list(
  itemStyle = list(color = htmlwidgets::JS("function(params){
    let cyl=params.value[3]; return (cyl==4 ? 'RoyalBlue' : cyl==6 ? 'OrangeRed':'green');}") ),
  selectedMode = 'multiple',
  select = list(itemStyle=list(color='magenta')), 
  emphasis = list(focus='self', blurScope='series'), # for brush rcv
  blur = list(opacity = 0.2)
))

bscols(
  list(
    div(style=styl, filter_checkbox("cyl", "Cylinders", sdf, ~cyl, inline=TRUE)),
    div(style=styl, filter_checkbox("gear", "Gears", sdf, ~gear, inline=TRUE)),
    filter_slider("hp", "Horsepower", sdf, ~hp, width = "100%"),
    d3scatter(sdf, ~mpg, ~wt, ~factor(cyl), width="100%", height=300),
    datatable(sdf, extensions="Scroller", style="bootstrap", class="compact", width="100%",
              options=list(deferRender=TRUE, scrollY=300, scroller=TRUE))
  ),  p
)

Brushing

echarty brush (sending) is controlled by the four toolbar options - Box, Lasso, Keep, Clear.
echarty can brush multiple areas by enabling Keep Selections from toolbar.
echarty will not ‘forget’ its selections if other remote selections are initiated. To clear all brush selections, click on an empty chart area or hit Box Clear from the toolbar.
Since remote brush (receiving) in echarty is done by highlight, any hover on chart points will downplay them all.

Filtering

Filter (send) in echarty is done by clicking on individual points one by one. We do not know of any box or lasso selection available.
Filtering is ‘stycky’ and once given control it won’t let go until all selected points have been deselected.
Test: select 5 in checkbox ‘Gears’, then in echarty unselect one of those (magenta) points. Now you need to unselect the remaining four to release the chart. You could also refresh the page to reset.

Notes

echarty with crosstalk has not been tested in Shiny.
ECharts GL/3D is a separate library used as a plugin. Currently it supports only brush-receive through echarty. There is a code sample in the gallery.
